kind.prompt:
You are building a Blazor Web App for a logistics company. The project has already been scaffolded at `/tmp/sv-465a4511d3b846e0b36363c39fd9abf4/ShipmentTracker/` using:

```
dotnet new blazor -n ShipmentTracker --interactivity WebAssembly --auth Individual --all-interactive
```

This gives us:
- Server project: `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker/` (hosts the app, has EF Core + SQLite + Identity)
- Client project: `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Client/` (WASM-rendered pages)

The solution file is at `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.sln`.

## Requirements
- Dispatchers view a list of shipments with status and destination
- Customers check their shipment status and estimated delivery
- Interactive WebAssembly render mode (already configured) — fast first paint via SSR prerendering, then WASM takes over for snappy client-side interactivity
- Individual account authentication (already configured)
- Role-based authorization: "Dispatcher" role and "Customer" role

## What to build

### 1. Shared Models (create `ShipmentTracker.Client/Models/`)

Create `Shipment.cs`:
```csharp
namespace ShipmentTracker.Client.Models;

public class ShipmentDto
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string TrackingNumber { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Origin { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Destination { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public ShipmentStatus Status { get; set; }
    public DateTime ShippedDate { get; set; }
    public DateTime EstimatedDelivery { get; set; }
    public string CustomerEmail { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}

public enum ShipmentStatus
{
    Pending,
    InTransit,
    OutForDelivery,
    Delivered,
    Delayed
}
```

### 2. Server-side Entity (create `ShipmentTracker/Data/Shipment.cs`)

```csharp
namespace ShipmentTracker.Data;

public class Shipment
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string TrackingNumber { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Origin { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Destination { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public ShipmentStatus Status { get; set; }
    public DateTime ShippedDate { get; set; }
    public DateTime EstimatedDelivery { get; set; }
    public string CustomerEmail { get; set; } = string.Empty;
}

public enum ShipmentStatus
{
    Pending,
    InTransit,
    OutForDelivery,
    Delivered,
    Delayed
}
```

### 3. Update `ApplicationDbContext` to include Shipments

Add `public DbSet<Shipment> Shipments => Set<Shipment>();` to the DbContext.

### 4. API Endpoints (add to server `Program.cs` before `app.Run()`)

Add a minimal API group for shipments:

```csharp
var shipments = app.MapGroup("/api/shipments").RequireAuthorization();

// GET all shipments (dispatchers only)
shipments.MapGet("/", async (ApplicationDbContext db) =>
{
    var items = await db.Shipments.OrderByDescending(s => s.ShippedDate).ToListAsync();
    return items.Select(s => new ShipmentDto { ... });
}).RequireAuthorization("DispatcherPolicy");

// GET shipment by tracking number (customers)
shipments.MapGet("/track/{trackingNumber}", async (string trackingNumber, ApplicationDbContext db, HttpContext http) =>
{
    var userEmail = http.User.FindFirstValue(System.Security.Claims.ClaimTypes.Email);
    var shipment = await db.Shipments.FirstOrDefaultAsync(s => s.TrackingNumber == trackingNumber && s.CustomerEmail == userEmail);
    if (shipment is null) return Results.NotFound();
    return Results.Ok(new ShipmentDto { ... });
});

// PUT update status (dispatchers only)
shipments.MapPut("/{id}/status", async (int id, ShipmentStatusUpdate update, ApplicationDbContext db) =>
{
    var shipment = await db.Shipments.FindAsync(id);
    if (shipment is null) return Results.NotFound();
    shipment.Status = update.Status;
    await db.SaveChangesAsync();
    return Results.Ok();
}).RequireAuthorization("DispatcherPolicy");

// POST create shipment (dispatchers only)
shipments.MapPost("/", async (CreateShipmentRequest request, ApplicationDbContext db) =>
{
    var shipment = new Shipment { ... };
    db.Shipments.Add(shipment);
    await db.SaveChangesAsync();
    return Results.Created($"/api/shipments/{shipment.Id}", ...);
}).RequireAuthorization("DispatcherPolicy");
```

Create helper record types in a new file `ShipmentTracker/Models/ApiModels.cs`:
```csharp
namespace ShipmentTracker.Models;
using ShipmentTracker.Data;

public record ShipmentStatusUpdate(ShipmentStatus Status);
public record CreateShipmentRequest(string TrackingNumber, string Origin, string Destination, DateTime EstimatedDelivery, string CustomerEmail);
```

Also add authorization policies in `Program.cs` after `builder.Services.AddAuthorization();`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthorizationBuilder()
    .AddPolicy("DispatcherPolicy", policy => policy.RequireRole("Dispatcher"));
```

Replace the existing `builder.Services.AddAuthorization();` line with this.

Add necessary usings to Program.cs: `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;`, `using System.Security.Claims;`, `using ShipmentTracker.Client.Models;`, `using ShipmentTracker.Models;`

### 5. Client-side Service (create `ShipmentTracker.Client/Services/ShipmentService.cs`)

```csharp
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using ShipmentTracker.Client.Models;

namespace ShipmentTracker.Client.Services;

public class ShipmentService(HttpClient http)
{
    public async Task<List<ShipmentDto>> GetAllShipmentsAsync()
    {
        var result = await http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<ShipmentDto>>("/api/shipments");
        return result ?? [];
    }

    public async Task<ShipmentDto?> TrackShipmentAsync(string trackingNumber)
    {
        var response = await http.GetAsync($"/api/shipments/track/{trackingNumber}");
        if (!response.IsSuccessStatusCode) return null;
        return await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<ShipmentDto>();
    }

    public async Task<bool> UpdateStatusAsync(int id, ShipmentStatus status)
    {
        var response = await http.PutAsJsonAsync($"/api/shipments/{id}/status", new { Status = status });
        return response.IsSuccessStatusCode;
    }

    public async Task<bool> CreateShipmentAsync(ShipmentDto shipment)
    {
        var response = await http.PostAsJsonAsync("/api/shipments", new
        {
            shipment.TrackingNumber,
            shipment.Origin,
            shipment.Destination,
            shipment.EstimatedDelivery,
            shipment.CustomerEmail
        });
        return response.IsSuccessStatusCode;
    }
}
```

### 6. Register HttpClient and ShipmentService in Client `Program.cs`

The client Program.cs should register:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddScoped(sp => new HttpClient { BaseAddress = new Uri(builder.HostEnvironment.BaseAddress) });
builder.Services.AddScoped<ShipmentTracker.Client.Services.ShipmentService>();
```

Also register in the server Program.cs for prerendering:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddScoped(sp => new HttpClient { BaseAddress = new Uri("https://localhost") });
builder.Services.AddScoped<ShipmentTracker.Client.Services.ShipmentService>();
```
(Add these after the existing service registrations, before `var app = builder.Build();`)

### 7. Blazor Pages (in `ShipmentTracker.Client/Pages/`)

Remove the default `Counter.razor` and `Weather.razor` pages if they exist.

**Create `Shipments.razor`** — Dispatcher dashboard (list all shipments, update status, create new):
- Route: `/shipments`
- `@attribute [Authorize(Roles = "Dispatcher")]`
- Shows a table of all shipments (tracking#, origin, destination, status, shipped date, estimated delivery, customer)
- Each row has a dropdown to change status
- A form at the top to create a new shipment
- Uses ShipmentService

**Create `Track.razor`** — Customer tracking page:
- Route: `/track`
- `@attribute [Authorize]`
- Has an input field for tracking number and a "Track" button
- Displays shipment details (status badge, origin, destination, estimated delivery) when found
- Shows "not found" message when tracking number doesn't match

### 8. Update Navigation (`NavMenu.razor` in `ShipmentTracker.Client/Layout/`)

Add nav links:
- "Shipments" → `/shipments` (with a truck/package icon)
- "Track Package" → `/track` (with a search icon)

Keep the Home link. Remove Counter and Weather links if present.

### 9. Seed Data

Create a `Data/SeedData.cs` in the server project that:
- Creates "Dispatcher" and "Customer" roles
- Creates a sample dispatcher user (dispatcher@shiptrack.com / Pass123!)
- Creates a sample customer user (customer@shiptrack.com / Pass123!)
- Seeds a few sample shipments

Call the seed method in Program.cs after `app` is built (use a scope to get services).

### 10. Create and apply EF migration

Run:
```bash
cd /tmp/sv-465a4511d3b846e0b36363c39fd9abf4/ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker
dotnet ef migrations add AddShipments -- --environment Development
```

If `dotnet-ef` is not installed, install it first:
```bash
dotnet tool install --global dotnet-ef
```

### 11. Update Home page

Update the Home page (either in server `Components/Pages/Home.razor` or client `Pages/Home.razor` — check which exists) to show a welcome message for the logistics app with links to the shipments dashboard and tracking page.

### 12. Build verification

After all changes, run:
```bash
cd /tmp/sv-465a4511d3b846e0b36363c39fd9abf4/ShipmentTracker
dotnet build ShipmentTracker.sln
```

Fix any build errors.

## Important Notes
- The `ShipmentDto` and `ShipmentStatus` enum in the Client project are the shared DTOs used by both client pages and server API.
- The server `Shipment` entity and `ShipmentStatus` enum are the EF Core models.
- Map between them in the API endpoints.
- Make sure the server-side `ShipmentStatus` enum values match the client-side ones.
- Add `@using ShipmentTracker.Client.Models` and `@using ShipmentTracker.Client.Services` to the client `_Imports.razor`.
- Use `System.Text.Json` serialization (the default).
- For the status enum serialization, use `[JsonConverter(typeof(JsonStringEnumConverter))]` on the enum OR ensure int serialization works on both sides. Simplest: just use int values.

Please implement all of this. Make sure the project builds successfully at the end.
